\end_inset

I'm not sure, but it could be a trap,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Winceham nodding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What choice is there?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned with a shrug.
 Winceham added:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

True, but I felt compelled to say that, just to make my point when things
 go horribly wrong.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ned placed a hand on Winceham's good shoulder and told him with ardor:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hurry, Wince.
 Be on your toes; try to hide yourself in the shadows up there.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Believe me when I say that would have been my first choice as well,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Winceham and sighed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two of them ran up the tower expecting some kind of surprise on the
 way, but nothing obstructed them.
 Soon, they emerged at the tower's top, the night sky glistening with starlight,
 the clouds below a soft, tempting, milky white mattress.
 They noticed alarmingly that the ship was missing, along with any signs
 of Theo and Bo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What really caught their eye though, was the way the sisters stood, not
 far away from the tower's edge right in front of the staircase.
 They were frozen like statues, the intensity of their plight drawn on their
 living faces.
 They looked as if a last, stilted breathe remained in them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Parcifal stood with Encelados blaring white hot above her head, both hands
 on the hilt, her face scrounged up in a mix of terror and hate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lernea was right beside her, calm like the sea, determined and unyielding
 as she was about to let an arrow fly; yet the bow's string remained taut,
 and Lernea stood there as if petrified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right behind the sisters stood an extremely tall, lavishly robed man with
 a beard, ruffled hair and a sharp, too sharp too be real, icy blue gleam
 on his eyes.
 Winceham tried to meld into the shadows, taking small back-steps to the
 nearest ledge of the tower, his hood over his head.
 The bearded man spoke then with a rolling, deep voice that sounded like
 stony reeds alongside a foaming river:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Now, now, Mr.
 Abbermouth.
 That would be futile, as much as it may hurt your ego.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hobb,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stated Ned coldly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well, yes.
 Among others,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said the man, the torch in his hand casting wild, creepy shadows of the
 two sisters as he silently and uncannily walked between them.
 Winceham noticed an unsettling thing about him: He wasn't actually walking;
 he was gliding a couple of inches above the stone floor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I hold you responsible for my father's death,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned and glared at him, heedless of how peculiar the man's voice and
 looks were, apart from the fact he was levitating.
 Hobb came to a stop a few yards away and smiled thinly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Weird things, humans.
 You blame me for your father's death, while Culliper pulled that trigger.
 Still, you couldn't kill him.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How do you know that?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked Ned with uneasy suspicion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I know many things.
 But what I crave right now is one: the amulet.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hobb's voice had a deadly finality to it.
 It took great composure and strength of character for a man to simply talk
 with that man around, yet Ned found in him the audacity to talk back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm not a jeweler; you have the wrong person.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hobb's face suddenly got screwed up horribly and stretched impossibly.
 With another twist of its flesh and a growling, the human face was torn
 away, evaporating instantly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In its place, an elongated head was now visible.
 Grey-blue skin shone slick in the starlight and a flock of stubby, short
 tentacles like anemones writhed around a circular, sharp-teethed maw.
 The hands had turned into webbed claws, sharp like scythes.
 Hobb, it turned out, was literally some kind of monster out of a nightmare.
 The creature that had disguised itself as Hobb looked at Ned with an irritated
 curiosity and blared ominously, its voice now grating:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Don't play coy with me! I know about your little escapades, and I've seen
 these females pathetic dreams! I couldn't care less.
 Where is the amulet?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

That's a really ugly way to ask for things,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned, while he noticed Winceham stood silent and immobile as a rock.
 Ned realised he was suddenly a little bit outmatched but carried on, trying
 to understand the foe in front of him and think of what to do next, really
 really fast.
 The creature approached him with unnerving silence and stood hovering in
 the air a few feet away.
 Its blue-on-blue eyes had the colour of the deepest sea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The comedian.
 Humor.
 How infantile.
 Not unlike your race.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Better infantile than have a mop for a face,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Ned told him and pointed to the maw.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You mock me? I am beyond mocking,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 replied the monster with a rumbling voice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Yes, I see mopping really is beneath you,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned grinning, gesturing at the tentacled maw.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You puny little human, you cannot begin to fathom the eons that have born
 me.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No, but I'm pretty sure you bore me,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned and noticed Winceham's eyes twitch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I was hoping I did not have to feed tonight; your minds sicken me,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the creature said and hissed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well, I could say the same thing about your face but that would be a compliment
 in your case,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 replied Ned, and saw Lernea's hand spasm ever so slightly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'll have what is mine, Ned Larkin, and you'll have what you deserve!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said the monster as he lunged forward with a gaping maw, aiming squarely
 for Ned's head, its powerful long arms springing to catch Ned in a deathly
 embrace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But it was right at that time that Lernea's arrow struck him in the back,
 causing it to turn around reflexively and growl, its maw tentacles writhing
 like the feet of a millipede.
 Ned slid away and ran towards the wheeled platform where the ship had docked.
 From the corner of his eye, he saw Lernea was trying to move and Parcifal's
 hands were trembling.
 Winceham too, could move his head again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I will find great delight in sucking your skull dry, Larkin!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cried the creature as it hurled himself against Ned, its robes fluttering
 in the night breeze.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

With your sense of humor, that's a no-brainer!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yelled Ned gleefully and saw Lernea, Parcifal and Winceham suddenly unfreeze
 completely.
 Without a second look at their surroundings, their weapons were being trained
 against the creature.
 Their angered shouts and brave cries rose into the night air.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

By Skarla, we'll have vengeance!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yelled the sisters, and Winceham asked before rushing towards the blue-skinned
 terror:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ya think you're tall, eh?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a wave of its hand and a low-keyed hum from its maw, all three of them
 were pushed back in the air.
 They landed hard on their backs, their weapons flying off their hands.
 The monster turned its attention squarely at Ned, before it added gleefully:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Where is the humor now, human?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last word had the subtle hints of sounding exactly like a writhing mass
 of worms would.
 Ned smiled coolly and retorted:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You just keep asking yourself, don't you?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The creature let out a terrible sound between an infuriated growl and a
 cacophonous gurgling laughter before it reached for Ned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Right when there was nothing funny to joke about, right about when Ned could
 see the others were still trying to get up, too far away to act, he saw
 Bo, the bunny with the flaming eyes jump right in front of him.
 Bo grinned at Ned widely and hopped back out of view in a split second,
 right before a hot molten cannonball hit the monster square across the
 face and embedded what was left of him and his smoldering robes in the
 tower's stony floor, a few feet away.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He then saw the ship wobbling uncertainly, sails rippling with small gusts
 of wind.
 Theo hurried to man the helm, while the bow cannon cooled with a red after-glow
 on its lip.
 A thin wisp of smoke wafted westward, where the wind blew.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ned smiled broadly and sighed with relief, while Winceham yelled as he looked
 around him, waiting for confirmation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Did ya see it? Did ya see the bunny?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sisters got up on their feet, nursing aching muscles and perhaps a couple
 of displaced bones.
 Lernea was about to say something to Winceham, but she lost her words when
 she saw a bright flash and an uncanny oval slit appear right above the
 tower floor in mid-air, at the place where the creature should have met
 its demise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slit made things look as if peering through a strange, stained looking
 glass, all broken and uneven.
 It was like someone had pieced together parts of another night sky; as
 if another place lay beyond that oval slit.
 The monster was limping heavily; it glanced at Ned and said nothing.
 Its eyes flashed suddenly, before it crossed into the oval slit, which
 then disappeared as strangely and abruptly as it had appeared.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ned stood there unable to really understand what had happened.
 So did the others, apart from Theo who, seemingly unfazed, settled the
 sloop near the platform a bit awkwardly.
 He jumped off the ship and quickly tied her down to the tower with a mooring
 line.
 He sounded awfully excited when he rushed over by Ned's side.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Wow! Did you see that? I think it left a crater on the floor!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Where were you?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked Ned weakly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well, that pirate was making weird noises like the ones people do when they
 die and Bo seemed really worried when the ship began to wobble real bad.
 He kind of insisted that I placed my amulet in this weird slot in that
 awful chair, and then all the wobbling stopped.
 But the pirate died,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 answered Theo truthfully, his voice trailing off with sadness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No, I mean, where were you when all this happened?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Oh, I heard this weird voice in my head and it felt all wrong; I was in
 the ship, where you told me to stay.
 But for some reason, Bo was already gnawing on that rope we had tied and
 before I could convince him otherwise, the ship had drifted away.
 So I thought I'd give her a spin,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Theo excitedly and added thoughtfully:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You did say I should keep an eye on her, didn't you?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Yes I did.
 I'm not sure though what would have happened if I hadn't.
 Or just what kind of a bunny Bo is, really,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned, ponderously gazing at Bo who was happily tucked away again inside
 Theo's robes, his face barely protruding, his nose twitching as if he was
 about to sneeze.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well what about that? You might be actually funny, lad.
 I think it saved our lives, to be honest.
 I couldn't flutter an eyelid, but everything you said, it just cracked
 me up for no reason! And then I could move again!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Winceham as he nourished a bruised elbow, grinning as he approached
 Ned and Theo.
 The sisters followed close behind, bickering about which one's fault some
 thing, or the other, really was.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

He, it, whatever, caught you by surprise!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Lernea accused Parcifal.
 The younger by one minute sister, replied in aggravated tones:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Me? You were the one who said to go have a look! Your decision, your responsibil
ity, your fault! I was simply carrying out your orders, my queen!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Only when it suits you, sister!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yelled Lernea, right about when Theo saw Culliper untying the rope that
 held the ship moored to the tower.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

He's trying to get away!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cried Theo and began to twirl his hands in the air for no apparent reason.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You didn't tie him down?!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked Ned in wild-eyed disbelief.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You told me to look after the ship, not him!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 replied Theo as the air between his hands began to fill with a warm, violet
 light.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Amateurs,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Winceham softly and picked up a loose cobblestone.
 He closed one eye and aimed at Culliper, just as he was about to start
 running back to the ship.
 Winceham threw the stone expertly and it connected with Culliper's head
 at a very accident-prone spot; the back of his head.
 Culliper staggered for a couple of steps, before collapsing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The violet light between Theo's hands died down softly; he and Ned walked
 over to where Culliper lay.
 He wasn't exactly unconscious, but he looked painfully disoriented.
 His face sported a furrowed grin, quite suitable for someone possibly brain
 damaged.
 Ned caught him by the nape of his jacket and told him more so, than asked
 him:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

We're not done yet.
 Where do you think you're going?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Tallyflop,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Culliper drowsily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Where's that?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked Ned and Culliper simply pointed up in the sky.
 Ned asked again, his voice giving off signals he wasn't in the mood for
 jokes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm not in the mood.
 Is that where the last shipment took the woodkin to?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Culliper nodded like a drunken chicken would.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Where is that?!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yelled Ned and still, a single finger pointed up into the sky.
 Theo asked rather calmly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The stars?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Culliper smiled like a five-year old boy and happily crumbled down on the
 platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It can't be.
 Off-world,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 remembered Ned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Why not?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked Theo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Flying is one thing.
 But the stars?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well I'm sure it's perfectly safe.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What is?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 asked Lernea, newly arrived over Culliper's unconscious body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Flying to the stars,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned and nodded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ridiculous!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Lernea with a scoff, while Parcifal commented with a curious smile
 on her lips:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No-one in our history has done that before, have they?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Winceham had only heard Parcifal speak, so he had to ask in turn:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What's never been done before?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Flying to the stars, to a place called Tallyflop, to save the woodkin and
 maybe get back at Hobb or whatever that thing was called,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ned, quietly gazing at the starry night sky.
 Winceham caught a glimpse of everyone contemplating this seriously, and
 after a moment or so of thinking, said with a sigh:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Maybe, just maybe, if I'm lucky enough, I'm still just having a bad trip.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

